<TITLE> Immigration to UK set to rise 30 percent </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Sept 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The number of people coming to live in Britain each year will be about 30 percent more than previously predicted, official figures suggest. The Office for National Statistics initially estimated the net increase in population due to migration would be 145,000 a year. But it raised that figure to 190,000 after taking account of the latest data, which included record levels of migration during 2004 and 2005. The long-term projection, until 2031, was revised as a result also of improved calculation methods. Home Secretary Jacqui Smith announced a toughening of migration rules at this week's Labour Party Conference. She told delegates a new deal would be signed during the next few days to toughen up checks carried out abroad on passengers travelling to the UK. "This will allow us to count people in, count people out, and prevent those we are concerned about from entering in the first place," she said. From March, an Australian-style points-based system will be introduced to restrict entry to those who have the skills that Britain needs. "We all know that the UK has not been alone in seeing higher levels of migration," Smith added. "We've seen the benefits, and we've faced the challenges of immigration and asylum head-on." Conservative immigration spokesman Damian Green attacked what he called the government's complacency. "This rips apart the government's previous complacent assumptions about net immigration," he said in a statement. Immigration Minister Liam Byrne said the report showed that swift and sweeping changes to the immigration system were needed in the next 12 mont
